#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
di-snapsend — Snapper-native Btrfs send/receive replication
===========================================================

A thin orchestration layer that replicates Snapper-created Btrfs snapshots from
the laptop to the server over SSH. It does NOT reimplement the Btrfs stream
format or the network transport — it shells out to:

    btrfs send [-p PARENT] SRC | [mbuffer |] ssh SERVER "sudo btrfs receive DST"

...and confines itself to the three things a wrapper actually has to get right:
snapshot enumeration, parent selection, and partial-transfer cleanup + retention.
btrfs does the hard filesystem + stream work, ssh does the (encrypted) network,
we do the bookkeeping.

This file is the implementation of the contract in di-snapsend-DESIGN.py and the
rationale in di-snapsend-SPEC.md. Read those for the *why*; this is the *what*.

CORRECTNESS MODEL (distilled from btrbk's source — the hard-won bits)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
(1) VALIDITY OF A RECEIVED SUBVOLUME — a subvolume EXISTING on the target does
    NOT mean the transfer completed. A clean receive is `readonly == true` AND
    `received_uuid` is set; a garbled one is writable with `received_uuid == '-'`.
    After every receive we verify both; if garbled we delete it ourselves.
    (Subvol.is_valid_received / Subvol.is_garbled)

(2) PARENT ELIGIBILITY ("correlation") — a source snapshot S may be the `-p`
    parent only if the server holds a snapshot correlated with S (same Btrfs
    lineage; both readonly). The parent for sending N is the NEWEST source
    snapshot that is both older than N and correlated with the target.
    (is_correlated / choose_parent)

(3) RETENTION PRUNE GUARD — retention must NEVER delete the newest correlated
    pair, because it is the parent the next incremental depends on. It is pinned.
    (_newest_correlated_pair pins; apply_retention honours it)

Correlation is by UUID, never by number, so Snapper churning/gapping the laptop
numbering under its own retention never breaks matching (SPEC §4).
"""

